proton pump","Competitively block histamine at H2 receptors on parietal cells","Inhibit histamine release from mast cells","Neutralise gastric acid"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EHistamine H2 receptor antagonists work by \u003Cstrong\u003Ecompetitively blocking histamine at H2 receptors on parietal cells\u003C/strong\u003E. This prevents histamine from binding and reduces activation of the proton pump, thereby decreasing gastric acid secretion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlockacetylcholine receptors on parietal cells\u003C/strong\u003E - This is not the mechanism of H2 antagonists. While acetylcholine does stimulate acid secretion via M3 receptors, H2 antagonists specifically target histamine receptors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirectly inhibit the proton pump\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes the mechanism of proton pump inhibitors, which act on the hydrogen-potassium ATPase enzyme.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibit histamine release from mast cells\u003C/strong\u003E - H2 antagonists act directly on parietal cells rather than affecting histamine release from other cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeutralise gastric acid\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes the mechanism of antacids, which chemically neutralise existing acid rather than preventing its secretion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBy blocking one of the three main stimulatory pathways for acid secretion (histamine, acetylcholine, and gastrin), H2 antagonists reduce but do not completely block acid production. This explains why they are less effective than proton pump inhibitors, which block the final common pathway of acid secretion.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Histamine H2 receptor antagonists work by competitively blocking histamine binding at H2 receptors on gastric parietal cells.","Blocking H2 receptors reduces gastric acid secretion by preventing histamine-stimulated activation of the proton pump.","H2 receptor antagonists are less effective than proton pump inhibitors at reducing gastric acid secretion."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54138"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17034"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54138","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54138"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-10T10:08:32+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-10T10:09:37+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9724"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68681"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"